Step Aside, Zoom... Google's Newly Revamped 'Meet' Is Now Free for Everyone

Anyone with a Gmail address can go full Brady Bunch (for free) with the latest and greatest Google videoconference service.

By Ruby Anderson

Published on 4/29/2020 at 2:19 PM

It kind of feels like the platform Zoom emerged from the ashes of our social lives overnight, becoming the clear video conference front-runner before most other options on the market were considered. But now this may finally change, because Google on Wednesday announced that it's making "Google Meet" free for anyone with a Gmail address. 

Where were you the first time someone asked you to Zoom? Before I was asked, I'd only heard of Google Hangouts Meet, which didn't allow custom backgrounds or grid views without the use of an extension. But Google recently copied some of Zoom's features and rebranded Hangouts Meet to just Meet, and today the company announced that its premium service will now be free for everyone. (Before today, anyone could join a Meet call, but only paying users could host a call.)



Two weeks ago, Google’s Vice President Javier Soltero told Reuters that Meet's new features include the option that arguably pushed us all towards Zoom--you could now have a crap ton of people presented in tile view at once. Meet previously only allowed four people, but now it's extending its tile view to 16 participants. Along with this welcomed change comes a new low-light mode, better noise cancelation, and the option to present only one Chrome tab instead of the whole screen. AKA, you can get freaky in your tabs again. 

Soltero wrote in a blog post that the company has focused on security and reliability during the development of Meet (Zoom was a little late to that game), and that in recent months they have "accelerated the release of top-requested features" to make the platform even better.

But Soltero warned users that they may not be able to access Meet right away. He wrote that, beginning next week, the company will be "gradually expanding" the platform's availability, but that users can sign up now and get notified when it's available.
